Modeling Political Risk Data¶

  • COMPSS 224B: Quantitative Political Risk
  • Authors: Iris Malone and Mark Rosenberg
  • Last Revised: 2 May 2025

This notebook will walk you through some basic non-parametric methods. This includes:

  • Class Imbalance
  • Tree Models
  • Hyperparameter tuning/grid search

Inspecting Your Data¶

In [2]:
singhway = pd.read_csv("singhway.csv")

Singh and Way (2004) examine the correlates of nuclear proliferation from 1945-2000. They want to understand why some states acquire a nuclear weapon (in a given year) versus others.

In [3]:
singhway.columns
Out[3]:
Index(['country', 'cowcc', 'year', 'risk', 'level', 'explore', 'pursue',
       'acquire', 'gdpcap', 'g2', 'industry1', 'rivalry', 'disputes', 'allies',
       'democracy', 'democratization', 'percentdems', 'openness',
       'liberalization'],
      dtype='object')

Correlates include:

  • Technological determinants:
    • gdp/cap,
    • gdp/cap^2,
    • industrial capacity index
  • External determinants:
    • rivalry,
    • militarized dispute involvement,
  • Internal determinants:
    • democracy,
    • democratization,
    • democratic ('good') neighborhood,
    • economic openness (exports as percent of gdp),
    • liberalization (change in trade ratios)

Distributions¶

In [5]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
def plot_histograms(df, bins=20, figsize=(15, 10), color='skyblue'):
    """
    Plots histograms for all numeric columns in the DataFrame.
    """
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns
    num_cols = len(numeric_cols)

    if num_cols == 0:
        print("No numeric columns to plot.")
        return

    cols = 3  # number of plots per row
    rows = (num_cols + cols - 1) // cols

    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols, 1):
        plt.subplot(rows, cols, i)
        df[col].hist(bins=bins, color=color, edgecolor='black')
        plt.title(col)
        plt.xlabel('Value')
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
plot_histograms(singhway.drop(['country', 'cowcc', 'year'], axis=1))
In [6]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

def plot_violin_plot(df, figsize=(15, 10)):
    """
    Generates side-by-side violin plots for each numeric column in a DataFrame.
    
    Args:
        df (pd.DataFrame): The input DataFrame.
        figsize (tuple): Size of the entire figure.
    """
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns
    num_cols = len(numeric_cols)

    if num_cols == 0:
        print("No numeric columns to plot.")
        return

    cols = 4  # plots per row
    rows = (num_cols + cols - 1) // cols

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=figsize)
    axes = axes.flatten()  # flatten in case of single row

    for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols):
        sns.violinplot(y=df[col], ax=axes[i], inner='box', linewidth=1)
        axes[i].set_title(f'Violin Plot: {col}')
        axes[i].set_ylabel(col)

    # Remove empty subplots if any
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
plot_violin_plot(singhway.drop(['country', 'cowcc', 'year'], axis=1))

Total Data¶

Singh and Way use a common country identifier known as 'Correlates of War' country code. We will translate it to more common iso2 format and add region identifiers

In [7]:
import country_converter as coco
cc = coco.CountryConverter()

# Add ISO 2-character and 3-character codes using src Gleditsch and Ward codes (pretty close)
singhway['iso2c'] = cc.convert(names=singhway['cowcc'], src='GWcode', to='ISO2')
singhway['iso3c'] = cc.convert(names=singhway['cowcc'], src='GWcode', to='ISO3')
singhway['region'] = cc.convert(names=singhway['iso2c'], src='ISO2', to='UNregion')

# Preview the result
print(singhway[['cowcc', 'iso2c', 'iso3c']].head())

def missing_values_table(df):
    mis_val = df.isnull().sum()
    mis_val_percent = 100 * df.isnull().sum() / len(df)
    mis_val_table = pd.concat([mis_val, mis_val_percent], axis=1)
    mis_val_table_ren_columns = mis_val_table.rename(
    columns = {0 : 'Missing Values', 1 : '% of Total Values'})
    mis_val_table_ren_columns = mis_val_table_ren_columns[
        mis_val_table_ren_columns.iloc[:,1] != 0].sort_values(
    '% of Total Values', ascending=False).round(1)
    
    print ("Your selected dataframe has " + str(df.shape[1]) + " columns.\n"      
        "There are " + str(mis_val_table_ren_columns.shape[0]) +
            " columns that have missing values.")
  
    return mis_val_table_ren_columns

# I also often use time series cross-sectional specific functions 
# to use in your own work modify by unit and date vars
def missing_country_table(df):
    df.reset_index(inplace=True)
    #df.drop(columns=['index', 'level_0'])
    mis_val = df.groupby(['iso2c']).apply(lambda x: x.isna().sum())
    mis_val_table = pd.concat([mis_val], axis=1)    
    return mis_val_table

#we'll add a new tool to inspect time series data
def missing_year_table(df):
    df.reset_index(inplace=True)
    #df.drop(columns=['index', 'level_0'])
    mis_val = df.groupby(['year']).apply(lambda x: x.isna().sum())
    mis_val_table = pd.concat([mis_val], axis=1)    
    return mis_val_table

# Train/test split (75% train, 25% test)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, train_size=0.8, random_state=2025)

# Fit logistic regression
model = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=1000)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict probabilities and classes
probs = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred = (probs > 0.5).astype(int)

# Mean squared error (MSE on probability prediction)
mse = np.mean((y_test - probs) ** 2)
print(f"Test MSE: {mse:.4f}")

# Confusion matrix
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Extract metrics
tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
accuracy = (tp + tn) / (tp + tn + fp + fn)
sensitivity = recall = tp / (tp + fn)  # recall
specificity = tn / (tn + fp)
precision = tp / (tp + fp)
f1 = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)

# Print results
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(cm)
# No Information Rate: proportion of majority class in y_test
nir = max(np.mean(y_test == 0), np.mean(y_test == 1))
print(f"No Information Rate (NIR): {nir:.3f}")
print(f"\nAccuracy:   {accuracy:.3f}")
print(f"Sensitivity (Recall): {sensitivity:.3f}")
print(f"Specificity: {specificity:.3f}")
print(f"Precision:   {precision:.3f}")
print(f"F1 Score:    {f1:.3f}")

Class Imbalance¶

When you have class imbalance you need to do feature selection before correcting for class imbalance If you try to correct after, then you'll have data leakage; the samples will be correlated which will artificially boost relative importance of indicators in sample

Commentary: SMOTE creates synthetic observations in the dataset. Even though the observations are synthetic, we actually see the highest sensitivity rate so far. SO what's the ``best'' model here? When we are correcting for class imbalance, we are generally assuming that we would prefer to maximize our sensitivity/recall rate rather than specificity (i.e. missing a true positive is more costly than missing a true negative). This is especially true in geopolitics where early warning monitors bank on accurately predicting tail risks ahead of time.

In [44]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

def evaluate_model(name, model, X_test, y_test):
    y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    y_pred = (y_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()

    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    prec = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    rec = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    spec = tn / (tn + fp)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    nir = max(np.mean(y_test == 0), np.mean(y_test == 1))

    print(f"\n{name} Evaluation:")
    print(f"Accuracy:    {acc:.3f}")
    print(f"Precision:   {prec:.3f}")
    print(f"Recall:      {rec:.3f}")
    print(f"Specificity: {spec:.3f}")
    print(f"F1 Score:    {f1:.3f}")
    print(f"No Information Rate: {nir:.3f}")

Grid Search and Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Suppose we want to optimize our RF and GBM models. To do this we want to grid search.

RF Grid Search¶

In [48]:
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=2025)
rf.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)
evaluate_model("Random Forest", rf, X_test, y_test)

Random Forest Evaluation:
Accuracy:    0.990
Precision:   0.333
Recall:      0.222
Specificity: 0.996
F1 Score:    0.267
No Information Rate: 0.992
In [49]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report


# Define hyperparameter grid
param_grid = {
    #number of trees
    #'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'n_estimators': list(range(100, 1001, 100)),
    #number of features m
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', 0.3, 0.5, None]  # None = all features
}

# Grid search with 5-fold CV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=rf,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=5,
    scoring='recall',  # or 'f1 'accuracy', 'roc_auc', etc.
    n_jobs=-1, #tells it to work in parallel to expedite
    verbose=1
)

# Fit on SMOTE-balanced training data
grid_search.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)

# Best estimator
best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_


# Print best parameters
print("Best params:", grid_search.best_params_)
# Evaluate using new parameters on test set
evaluate_model("Random Forest (Tuned)", best_rf, X_test, y_test)

Fitting 5 folds for each of 50 candidates, totalling 250 fits
Best params: {'max_features': 'sqrt', 'n_estimators': 100}

Random Forest (Tuned) Evaluation:
Accuracy:    0.990
Precision:   0.333
Recall:      0.222
Specificity: 0.996
F1 Score:    0.267
No Information Rate: 0.992

Commentary Recall rate is lower, but precision and F1 is higher than logit. Why? It means there is probably strong class interdependences in features, dataset is too small, or true relationships are linear. For example, maybe there is baseline amount of resources that major powers must possess to pursue a nuclear weapons program. There are so many zeros for these smaller countries that they don't even stand a chance (in which case maybe we'd be better off thinking of a hurdle or neural network).

GBM Grid Search¶

In [51]:
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define XGBoost model
xgb = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, 
                    eval_metric='logloss', 
                    random_state=2025)

# Hyperparameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': list(range(100, 1001, 100)),  # number of trees
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],      # shrinkage
    'max_depth': [2, 4, 6, 8]                     # interaction depth
}

# Grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=5,
    scoring='recall',  # or 'f1', 'accuracy', 'roc_auc'
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=1
)

# Fit on SMOTE-balanced training data
grid_search.fit(X_train_smote, y_train_smote)

# Best model
best_xgb = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Print best parameters
print("Best XGBoost params:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Evaluate on test set
evaluate_model("XGBoost (Tuned)", best_xgb, X_test, y_test)

Commentary: F1 score is better than lgoit because recall rate is better. So does that mean it's the better model? The metric you choose to evaluate really depends on the prediction problem and the audience. If I want to make sure I avoid accidentally starting a nuclear war by preemptively targeting a counry then maybe recall is important. But if I want an early warning system, than maybe recall is less important than precision.
